# Intervals of Real Numbers — Full Explanation 😊

---

## The KEY difference — Brackets vs Parentheses

| Symbol | Meaning | Includes endpoint? |
|---|---|---|
| **[ ]** Square bracket | CLOSED | ✅ YES included |
| **( )** Round bracket | OPEN | ❌ NO not included |

---

## All Interval Types Explained

### 1️⃣ Closed Interval [a, b]
$$[a,b] = a \leq x \leq b$$
```
●————————●
a                b
```
- **Both a and b are INCLUDED** ✅
- The dots are FILLED ●

---

### 2️⃣ Half Open [a, b)
$$[a,b) = a \leq x < b$$
```
●————————○
a                b
```
- a included, b NOT included

---

### 3️⃣ Half Open (a, b]
$$(a,b] = a < x \leq b$$
```
○————————●
a                b
```
- a NOT included, b included

---

### 4️⃣ Open Interval (a, b)
$$(a,b) = a < x < b$$
```
○————————○
a                b
```
- **Neither a nor b included** ❌

---

### 5️⃣ Infinity Intervals
$$[a, \infty) = a \leq x$$
$$(a, \infty) = a < x$$
$$(-\infty, b] = x \leq b$$
$$(-\infty, b) = x < b$$

> **Infinity ALWAYS gets ( ) round bracket** because infinity is never actually reached! ♾️

---

### 6️⃣ All Real Numbers
$$(-\infty, \infty) = \mathbb{R}$$
- Simply means **every number** exists here!

---

## Simple Memory Trick 🧠

```

[ ] = CLOSED door = you CAN enter (included)
( ) = OPEN door   = you CANNOT enter (excluded)
```

---

## Complete Summary Table

| Interval | Meaning | a included? | b included? |
|---|---|---|---|
| [a, b] | a ≤ x ≤ b | ✅ | ✅ |
| [a, b) | a ≤ x < b | ✅ | ❌ |
| (a, b] | a < x ≤ b | ❌ | ✅ |
| (a, b) | a < x < b | ❌ | ❌ |
| [a, ∞) | a ≤ x | ✅ | — |
| (a, ∞) | a < x | ❌ | — |
| (-∞, b] | x ≤ b | — | ✅ |
| (-∞, b) | x < b | — | ❌ |
| (-∞, ∞) | all reals | — | — |

